## ğŸ” `grep` â€” The Pattern Finder
grep [options] PATTERN [FILE...]

- Search for patterns inside files.
- Flags:
  - `-i`: ignore case
  - `-r`: recursive
  - `-v`: invert match
  - `-E`: extended regex
  

**Example:**
```bash
grep -i "error" /var/log/syslog
grep 'error' /var/log/syslog
grep -i 'saâ€™shel' users.txt
grep -v '^#' config.conf  # Exclude comments
grep -r '192.168' /etc/network





âœ‚ï¸ sed â€” Stream Editor
Reads input line-by-line and applies transformations (substitution, deletion, insertion).
sed [options] 'command' file

Common Commands:

s/pattern/replacement/ â€“ Substitute

/pattern/d â€“ Delete matching lines

-n 'N,p' â€“ Print only specific lines

-i â€“ Edit files in-place

Delimiter flexibility: Use : or | instead of / if the pattern contains slashes.

Special Characters:

$ â€“ End of line

^ â€“ Start of line

	â€¢	Edit files or streams with patterns.
	â€¢	Common actions:
	â€¢	Substitution: s/old/new/
	â€¢	Deletion: /pattern/d
	â€¢	Print specific lines: -n '2,4p'

Example: sed 's/foo/bar/g' file.txt


ğŸ“Š awk â€” Text Analysis Beast
	â€¢	Reads and processes columns and rows (like a mini spreadsheet). ğŸ“Š awk â€“ Text Scanning & Reporting

What it does:
awk 'pattern { action }' file
Processes structured text using patterns and actions. Great for columns.
	â€¢	Fields: $1, $2, â€¦, $NF
	â€¢	Custom separators: -F ","
awk -F ":" '{ print $1 " => " $7 }' /etc/passwd
Built-in Variables:

$1, $2, ..., $NF: Fields (columns)

NF: Number of fields

NR: Number of records (lines)

FS: Field Separator

OFS: Output Field Separator
Examples:
awk '{ print $1 }' users.txt
awk -F":" '{ print $1, $7 }' /etc/passwd
awk 'BEGIN { FS=","; OFS=" - " } { print $2, $1 }' users.csv
awk '$1 ~ /Sa/ && NF == 3 { print $0 }' users.txt

ğŸ” Regular Expressions (Regex)

Used in grep, awk, sed, and vim.

Basics:
	â€¢	. â€” any character
	â€¢	^ â€” start of line
	â€¢	$ â€” end of line
	â€¢	[] â€” match set of characters
	â€¢	.* â€” wildcard
	â€¢	\ â€” escape character
 What it does:

Describes string patterns for powerful matching logic.

Basic Meta-characters:

. â€“ Any character

* â€“ Zero or more

+ â€“ One or more (use with grep -E)

? â€“ Zero or one

^ â€“ Start of line

$ â€“ End of line

[] â€“ Match any one character inside brackets

[^] â€“ Match any one character NOT inside brackets

| â€“ OR operator


grep "^Sa" users.txt
grep '^Sa' names.txt         # Starts with "Sa"
grep 'sh.*el' names.txt      # Match sh...el (wildcard)
grep '[0-9]' file.txt        # Contains a number
grep '[^a-zA-Z]' file.txt    # Contains non-letter

Used In:

grep for pattern search

sed for find/replace

awk for conditional logic

vim for searching/editing text

